Aloha
HAWAII'S GREATEST PAGEANT • October 30 to November 6, 1949
Week

• It's the Mardi Gras, Frontier Days,
and New Year's Eve-all packed
into one great week of thrilling entertainment
you'll never forget! During this
spectacular Hawaiian holiday, or
"Makabiki"
Honolulu shuns business attire to blossom forth in all the
color and gaiety of a tropical rainbow.
• Gardenias and flaming hibiscus appear in every
hairdress. Fragrant plumeria and carnation leis encircle shoulders
of visitor and Islander alike...and everywhere is
the brightly flowered holoku-the picturesque formal dress
of early Hawaii, and the tapa-patterned "aloha" shirt.
• Each day of Aloha Week presents authentic pageants depicting
highlights of Hawaiian history... the landing of
King Kamehameha I... installation ceremony for Hawaiian
chieftains...ancient dancing and sporting events... and early village life.
Evenings are just as eventful. You'll
attend hula pageants, native luaus (feasts),
and dance under the stars at famous
clubs and hotels. A holiday you'll talk about
for years to come!
